sub_subject.name: Discrete Mathematics (Computer Science & Logic Bridge)
sub_subject.description: 13-year academic progression (K-12) for Discrete Mathematics (Computer Science & Logic Bridge) (Mathematics)

objectives.objective_text: Identify choices (red shirt or blue shirt).
Recall that if we have 3 birds and 2 houses, they must share.
Identify a group of items (e.g., red toys).
Name an item that belongs to a group.
Identify the middle part where hoops overlap.
Recall that we can mix and match.
Identify the degree of a vertex (how many lines touch it).
Identify 'Or' means one or the other.
Identify when two statements mean the same thing.
Recall that a different order makes a new pattern.
List all ways to arrange 3 items.
Summarize the rule: If items $>$ boxes, one box has more than one.
Defend the certainty of the conclusion.
Defend the logic of the fundamental counting principle.
Recall that we can count forever.
Recall that a set is a collection.
Observe that some things don't belong.
List members of a set using braces { }.
Recall that one thing can be two things (red AND square).
Explain how to find the next row (add numbers above).
Summarize the Multiplication Rule (3 shirts $\times$ 2 pants = 6 outfits).
Explain the Addition Rule (soup OR salad).
Draw a tree diagram to show choices.
Recall that 'All dogs bark' might be true.
Explain the symmetry of the coefficients.
Defend the relationship to the normal distribution.
Change the order of beads on a string.
Summarize Order Matters (Combination lock) vs. Doesn't Matter (Fruit salad).
Explain rearranging letters in a word.
Explain why $nCr$ is always smaller than $nPr$.
Defend the choice of method based on problem context.
Fill in a simple table for AND.
Summarize the rule for a set (e.g., even numbers).
Place numbers in the correct region.
Interpret graphical representations of the principle.
Connect to proving existence without finding the specific instance.
Explain a 'Weighted' graph (numbers on the lines).
Defend the foundational nature of logic in math.
Count how many are in the group.
Defend Cantor's contribution to understanding infinity.
Explain that an 'Element' is one piece of the set.
Defend the foundational role of sets in modern mathematics (ZFC).
Find items that are in both groups (red AND round).
Summarize how a Venn Diagram works.
Explain how to use Venns for solving logic puzzles.
Defend the limitations of Venns for 4+ sets.
Explain how GPS finds a route.
Schedule classes so they don't overlap (coloring problem).
Trace a shape without lifting the pencil.
Try not to cross a line.
Summarize the Seven Bridges of Knigsberg problem.
Explain an Euler Path (visit every edge once).
Try to draw the 'envelope' shape without lifting pen.
Explain why some graphs are impossible to trace.
Defend the historical significance of Euler's solution.
Summarize a Graph (dots and lines, not a chart).
Defend the utility of graphs for modeling relationships.
Follow a path on a directed graph.
Defend the use of DAGs (Directed Acyclic Graphs) in scheduling.
Explain that in math, OR usually includes both.
Defend the truth values of the material implication.
Summarize a Proposition (a sentence that is T or F).
Explain why 'What time is it?' is not a proposition.
Determine the truth value of a statement.
Explain the Law of Excluded Middle.
Summarize Universal (Every) vs. Existential (At least one).
Explain how to disprove 'All' (find one counterexample).
Explain nested quantifiers (Every pot has a lid).
Defend the rigor of predicate logic.
Follow a rule to find the answer.
Summarize a Truth Table (listing all possibilities).
Explain De Morgan's Laws via tables.
Analyze the connection between Pascal's Triangle and Combinations.
Connect probability of coin flips to binomial coefficients.
Prove that two people in a big crowd have the same hair count (concept).
Compare the size of two finite sets.
Interpret the Principle of Inclusion-Exclusion for two sets.
Connect one-to-one correspondence to comparing sizes.
Interpret the symbol $\in$ (is an element of).
Connect subsets ($\subseteq$) to the parent set.
Interpret word problems using set logic.
Defend the logic of boolean algebra.
Evaluate problems with restrictions (e.g., 'must sit together').
Interpret Critical Path Analysis in project management.
Connect graph coloring to map making (4 Color Theorem).
Analyze Euler's Theorem (based on vertex degree).
Interpret a Hamilton Cycle (visit every vertex once).
Connect the Traveling Salesman Problem to Hamilton cycles.
Connect dots to make a shape.
Connect graphs to map coloring problems.
Interpret a flowchart as a directed graph.
Interpret negated quantifiers (Not All = Some are not).
Analyze truth tables for compound statements.
Interpret Tautologies (always true) and Contradictions (always false).
Connect truth tables to proving equivalence.
Evaluate specific terms in a high-power expansion.
Construct rigorous proofs using the principle.
Synthesize discrete math logic with proof writing.
Evaluate the Power Set of a given set.
Evaluate complex operations involving three or more sets.
Evaluate survey data using Venn regions.
Evaluate the robustness of a network.
Evaluate the complexity of finding Hamilton cycles (NP-complete).
Evaluate the truth of complex statements.
Evaluate the truth of quantified statements over specific domains.
Evaluate the validity of an argument form.
Construct the full binomial expansion using sigma notation.
Defend the use of graph algorithms in social media analysis.
Construct arguments about the cardinality of the rationals vs. reals.
Synthesize theological concepts of the Infinite with mathematical models.
Construct formal proofs of set identities.
Synthesize set operations with probability rules.
Construct Venn diagrams to prove set identities.
Synthesize counting rules with algebraic formulas.
Construct a network model for a logistics problem.
Synthesize logic gates in circuitry using standard logic gate symbols.
Construct formal logical statements using quantifiers.
Synthesize proof writing with quantifier logic.
Synthesize digital logic design with truth tables.
Synthesize algebraic proof with combinatorial identity.
Synthesize visual logic with algebraic set theory.
Synthesize matrix algebra with graph theory.
Synthesize algorithmic thinking with real-world constraints.
Construct algorithms to find Eulerian circuits.
